handled\n- now you need to implement the backspace key and remove the last character. simple, right? except that utf-8 exists so you have to make sure to subtract a character rather than a byte, else whatever you're using for rendering might crash from an invalid sequence\n- now you need to implement the cursor. you need to always append and delete characters _at_ the cursor's position, and update the position after you've done so.\n  - don't forget about the edgecase of backspacing at the start of a string!\n- now make the cursor movable with arrow keys. that's it, right? nope! don't forget the Home and End keys send you to the left or right of a line, respectfully. of a _line_. not the whole string. make sure to render the cursor correctly by evaluating the slice of the string that's behind the cursor and rendering it where it ends\n  - as a bonus exercise implement mouse support so you can click to move it around\n- oh, and you haven't forgotten about newlines, right?\n- right, now the text needs to be selectable. people more commonly use the mouse for selecting than keyboards so make sure to have that implemented by now. implement highlighting the slice that's selected, make sure not to forget about being able to go _back_ from where the selection started, or using Home\u002FEnd for the selection while holding shift. also don't forget ctrl+a!\n  - did you know you can double click on a word to select it\n- don't forget backspace while selecting something should only delete the selection! and typing something should also do the same\n- now add copy-pasting. ctrl+x, ctrl+c, ctrl+v, etc. but wait, what are you using for the inputs? the same input system you've got for the rest of your program? oh don't be silly, ctrl+c\u002Fv must match the user's layout instead of ignoring it for consistency between how most people implement it"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"i'm probably forgetting something but like. do you see. do you see why this sucks"}}],"plainTextBody":"- like, ok. what does a textfield consist of? it consists of you being able to type text. so let's make it so keypress inputs append to some string and render it.\n- except depending on whatever engine you're using, this may return full strings (like `esc` for escape, `space` for space and whatnot) or return QWERTY key names. but let's say you have that handled\n- now you need to implement the backspace key and remove the last character. simple, right? except that utf-8 exists so you have to make sure to subtract a character rather than a byte, else whatever you're using for rendering might crash from an invalid sequence\n- now you need to implement the cursor. you need to always append and delete characters _at_ the cursor's position, and update the position after you've done so.\n  - don't forget about the edgecase of backspacing at the start of a string!\n- now make the cursor movable with arrow keys. that's it, right? nope! don't forget the Home and End keys send you to the left or right of a line, respectfully. of a _line_. not the whole string. make sure to render the cursor correctly by evaluating the slice of the string that's behind the cursor and rendering it where it ends\n  - as a bonus exercise implement mouse support so you can click to move it around\n- oh, and you haven't forgotten about newlines, right?\n- right, now the text needs to be selectable. people more commonly use the mouse for selecting than keyboards so make sure to have that implemented by now. implement highlighting the slice that's selected, make sure not to forget about being able to go _back_ from where the selection started, or using Home\u002FEnd for the selection while holding shift. also don't forget ctrl+a!\n  - did you know you can double click on a word to select it\n- don't forget backspace while selecting something should only delete the selection! and typing something should also do the same\n- now add copy-pasting. ctrl+x, ctrl+c, ctrl+v, etc. but wait, what are