<!-- --><li>like, ok. what does a textfield consist of? it consists of you being able to type text. so let&#x27;s make it so keypress inputs append to some string and render it.<!-- --></li>
<!-- --><li>except depending on whatever engine you&#x27;re using, this may return full strings (like <!-- --><code>esc<!-- --></code> for escape, <!-- --><code>space<!-- --></code> for space and whatnot) or return QWERTY key names. but let&#x27;s say you have that handled<!-- --></li>
<!-- --><li>now you need to implement the backspace key and remove the last character. simple, right? except that utf-8 exists so you have to make sure to subtract a character rather than a byte, else whatever you&#x27;re using for rendering might crash from an invalid sequence<!-- --></li>
<!-- --><li>now you need to implement the cursor. you need to always append and delete characters <!-- --><em>at<!-- --></em> the cursor&#x27;s position, and update the position after you&#x27;ve done so.
<!-- --><ul>
<!-- --><li>don&#x27;t forget about the edgecase of backspacing at the start of a string!<!-- --></li>
<!-- --></ul>
<!-- --></li>
<!-- --><li>now make the cursor movable with arrow keys. that&#x27;s it, right? nope! don&#x27;t forget the Home and End keys send you to the left or right of a line, respectfully. of a <!-- --><em>line<!-- --></em>. not the whole string. make sure to render the cursor correctly by evaluating the slice of the string that&#x27;s behind the cursor and rendering it where it ends
<!-- --><ul>
